04759nam a22005295i 9780520351981DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19891989cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203519817 a10.1525/97805203519812doi  a(DE-B1597)649083  a(OCoLC)1414456282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aBooth, Wayne C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCompany We Keep :bAn Ethics of Fiction /cWayne C. Booth; ed. by Wayne C. Booth. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1989] 4cÂ©1989  a1 online resource (580 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPART I -- tRELOCATING ETHICAL CRITICISM -- t1 Introduction: Ethical Criticism, a Banned Discipline? -- t2 Why Ethical Criticism Fell on Hard Times -- t3 The Peculiar "Logic" of Evaluative Criticism -- t4 The Threat of Subjectivism and the Ethics of Craft -- t5 Who Is Responsible in Ethical Criticism, and for What? -- tPart II -- tTHE MAKING OF FRIENDS AND COMMONWEALTHS Criticism as Ethical Culture -- tIntroduction: The Turn to Self-culture -- t6 Implied Authors as Friends and Pretenders -- t7 Appraising Some Friends -- t8 Consequences for Character The Faking and Making of the "Self" -- t9 Appraising Character: Desire against Desire -- t10 Figures That "Figure" the Mind: Images and Metaphors as Constitutive Stories -- t11 Metaphoric Worlds: Myths, Their Creators and Critics -- tPART III -- tDoctrinal Criticism and the Redemptions of Coduction -- tIntroduction -- t12 Rabelais and the Challenge of Feminist Criticism -- t13 Doctrinal Questions in Jane Austen, D. H. Lawrence, and Mark Twain -- tEPILOGUE The Ethics of Reading -- tAPPENDIX An Anthology of Ethical Gifts, Thank-you Notes, and Warnings -- tBibliography of Ethical Criticism -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Names and Titles0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Company We Keep, Wayne C. Booth argues for the relocation of ethics to the center of our engagement with literature.But the questions he asks are not confined to morality. Returning ethics to its root sense, Booth proposes that the ethical critic will be interested in any effect on the ethos, the total character or quality of tellers and listeners. Ethical criticism will risk talking about the quality of this particular encounter with this particular work. Yet it will give up the old hope for definitive judgments of "good" work and "bad." Rather it will be a conversation about many kinds of personal and social goods that fictions can serve or destroy. While not ignoring the consequences for conduct of engaging with powerful stories, it will attend to that more immediate topic, What happens to us as we read? Who am I, during the hours of reading or listening? What is the quality of the life I lead in the company of these would-be friends?Through a wide variety of periods and genres and scores of particular works, Booth pursues various metaphors for such engagements: "friendship with books," "the exchange of gifts," "the colonizing of worlds," "the constitution of commonwealths." He concludes with extended explorations of the ethical powers and potential dangers of works by Rabelais, D. H. Lawrence, Jane Austen, and Mark Twain.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aSemiotics & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBooth, Wayne C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052006210840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035198140u